import java.util.*;  // Importing the necessary classes for List, Set...etc in Java

public class java_45208_CredentialValidator_A01 {     // Declaring a new public static credential validator named passwordvalidator (A Credential Validators are like an Authentication Service)  
    private final String PASSWORD_PATTERN =  "^(?=.*[0-9])(?=.*[a-z])(?=.*[A-Z]).{8,}$";  //Defining a pattern to ensure the password contains at least one digit (digit), lowercase and upper case.
     public boolean validatePassword(String input) {   //This function will accept an argument which is presumably User's Password; if it validates successfully then return true otherwise false or error message  .    Returns a Boolean value, indicating whether the password meets all conditions: minimum length (8 characters), at least one digit and lower/upper case letter.
         //returning result of check with input parameter   ;Check is made on each condition separately because if any fails it returns 'false' otherwise true or error message to be printed out in such cases  . The password should match the pattern, ie., contain at least one digit (digit), lowercase and upper case.
         //It means that user entered "password" not matching with required format of having minimum length as greater than equal to '8', containing a character from both small letter ('a' -> lowecase) & large letters('A'->uppercases).  This is how A01_BrokenAccessControl vulnerability can be demonstrated.
         return inputMatches(input,PASSWORD_PATTERN);   // calling function to check password match with the pattern and returning result of that operation which will either true or false (true if matched else False) .  It is not really a CredentialValidator per se as it's used for authentication but could be an example program in demonstrating security sensitive operations.
     }    //Ending class definition & method declaration part   public static and return type must match with the one that function returns otherwise compilation error may occur .  Must use same datatypes to compare which is String, boolean etc., because Java treats them differently (String data types are Immutable). For instance 'return inputMatches(input.toUpperCase(),PASSWORD_PATTERN);' will not compile as it attempts converting the string into uppercase and then comparing if password matches with pattern or else returning Boolean value which might lead to unexpected results in this case because of different casing conventions for characters (lowercase,uppercases)  
}  //Ends Class Definition. It must be followed by a semicolon (;). If not present it will result into errors due to the way Java treats method declaration and class definition which is why I included them in this response . This line 'return false;' should have been there but instead of that, return type could match with what validatePassword function returns (which can be true or error message) as per your requirement.